Is automatic or manual transmission better for MPG?

Bankbintje

17th august 2015

Executive Summary

The magazine Motor Trend is interested in exploring the relationship between a set of variables and miles per gallon (MPG). They are particularly interested in the following two questions:

  • “Is an automatic or manual transmission better for MPG?”
  • “Quantify the MPG difference between automatic and manual transmissions”

A simple hypothesis test confirms that a significant difference in fuel efficiency does exist between cars with automatic transmission and cars with manual transmission. Simple linear regression Multivariate regression

Several multivariate models were fitted and compared. The selected model showed the Choose a model by AIC in a Stepwise Algorithm Adjusted R^2

Linear regression models were fitted, with various number of variables, and compared between each other based on the adjusted R2. The best model was based on car weight and number of cylinders (+ intercept), which explained 81.2% of variability in the MPG data. The impact of transmission on residuals was close to zero and highly insignificant. We conclude, that given the same weight and number of cylinders in the car, transmission doesn’t have any impact on fuel efficiency.

Data

Exploratory Data Analysis

This analysis is based on the mtcars dataset from the base r datasets-package. The data was extracted from the 1974 Motor Trend US magazine, and comprises fuel consumption and 10 aspects of automobile design and performance for 32 automobiles (1973–74 models).

data=mtcars

The appendix (tabels 1-4) contains the results of some basic data exploration. Main conclusions are that the data does not seem to contain missing values and/or clear outliers. Furthermore, there is a marked difference in fuel consumption (mpg) per Transmission Type. (see appendix, plot 2) Most importantly, the distribution of fuel consuption (mpg) appears normal, this allows for fitting a linear model. (see appendix, plot 1)

Cleaning Data

The dataset is tidy and needs no major cleaning. The variables am, cyl, vs and gear will be converted to factors, the values 0 and 1 for transmssion type will be replaced by “Automatic” and “Manual”.

mtcars.clean<-mtcars
mtcars.clean$am <- as.factor(mtcars$am)
mtcars.clean$cyl <- as.factor(mtcars$cyl)
mtcars.clean$vs <- as.factor(mtcars$vs)
mtcars.clean$gear <- as.factor(mtcars$gear)
levels(mtcars.clean$am) <-c("Automatic", "Manual")

Hypothesis testing

First we will check if cars with automatic transmission actually use more gas than cars with manual transmission. A simple boxplot shows that this appears to be the case. (see appendix, plot 2) Running a Welch Two Sample t-test could confirm whether the difference is significant and whether we can reject our null-hypothesis: no significant difference exists between cars with automatic transmission and cars with manual transmission.

t.test(mtcars.clean[mtcars.clean$am == "Automatic",]$mpg, 
       mtcars.clean[mtcars.clean$am == "Manual",]$mpg)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  mtcars.clean[mtcars.clean$am == "Automatic", ]$mpg and mtcars.clean[mtcars.clean$am == "Manual", ]$mpg
## t = -3.7671, df = 18.332, p-value = 0.001374
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -11.280194  -3.209684
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  17.14737  24.39231

The low p-value (0.001374) indicates that the probability that this difference is accidental is very low; the difference is significant and the null-hypothesis can be rejected. The confidence interval tells us how much lower the mpg is in cars with manual transmission from cars with automatic transmission - thus between 3.2 and 11.3 MPG lower in 95% of the cases. For further quantifying the effect we will apply linear regression.

Regression on a single variable

The full results of regression of fuel consumtion (mpg) on transmission type (am) are shown in the appendix.

Conlusions on this model are that

fit1<-lm(mpg ~ am, data=mtcars.clean)

The coefficents and adjusted R^2 value:

summary(fit1)$coef
##              Estimate Std. Error   t value     Pr(>|t|)
## (Intercept) 17.147368   1.124603 15.247492 1.133983e-15
## amManual     7.244939   1.764422  4.106127 2.850207e-04
summary(fit1)$adj.r.squared
## [1] 0.3384589

p-value: 0.000285 The null hypothesis is rejected by p-value = 0.000285 but the regression model covers only 36% of the variance.

So, the model coefficients are:

intercept = 17.15 represents automatic cars mean mpg am coefficient = 7.24 represents the adjusted estimate for the expected change in mpg comparing AT versus MT.

Multivariate Regression

lm(formula = mpg ~ wt + qsec + am, data = mtcars.clean)
